The game received mixed reviews. It received 97% and 92% ratings from [[Zzap!64]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Bombuzal review|publisher=[[Zzap!64|Zzap]]|issue=44|pages=18–19|author1=Maff Evans |author2=Paul Glancey |author3=Kati Hamza |date=December 1988}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Bombuzal review|publisher=[[Zzap!64|Zzap]]|issue=45|pages=103|author1=Gordon Houghton |author2=Kati Hamza |date=January 1989}}</ref> magazine for the C64 and Amiga versions respectively, compared to a review in [[Commodore User]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Bombuzal review|publisher=[[Commodore User]]|pages=26–27|author=Tony Dillon|date=November 1988}}</ref> magazine awarding a mere 49%. The former reviews applaud it as an addictive puzzle game with "cute" graphics, while the latter criticizes gameplay, graphics, and controls.

The game was released by Spotlight Software and distributed by [[Cinemaware]] in the compilation ''BrainBlaster'' with ''[[Xenon 2]]'' for the [[Amiga]]. This compilation was reviewed in 1991 in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' #165 by Hartley, Patricia, and Kirk Lesser in "The Role of Computers" column. The reviewers gave ''BrainBlaster'' 5 out of 5 stars.<ref name="Dragon165">{{Citation
